******
[1] China, 5th death
Date: Thu 4 Apr 2013
Source: US Today, Associated Press report [edited]
http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/04/04/bird-flu-china/2052891/


A middle-aged man who transported poultry for a living and another unidentified person have died from a new strain of bird flu, bringing the death toll to 5 among 14 confirmed cases in China, the government and state media reported Thursday [4 Apr 2013]. The 48-year-old man, who died in Shanghai, is one of several among the infected believed to have had direct contact with fowl. Until recently, the virus, called H7N9, was not known to infect humans. The official Xinhua News Agency did not identify the 5th fatality, but said that person also died in Shanghai on Wednesday [3 Apr 2013]. It said the Ministry of Agriculture confirmed on Thursday [4 Apr 2013] that the H7N9 virus had been detected in pigeons at a market selling agricultural products in Shanghai.

It is not known how people are becoming sick with the virus, but health officials and scientists caution that there are no indications it can be transmitted from one person to another. Scientists who have studied the virus's genetic sequence said this week that the virus may have mutated, spreading more easily to other animals and potentially posing a bigger threat to humans.

Guidelines issued Wednesday [3 Apr 2013] by the national health agency identify butchers, breeders and sellers of poultry, and those in the meat processing industry as at higher risk. Experts only identified the 1st cases on Sunday [31 Mar 2013]. Some among the 14 confirmed cases fell ill several weeks ago but only now are being classified as having H7N9. Xinhua said 6 cases have been confirmed in Shanghai, 4 in Jiangsu, 3 in Zhejiang, and one in Anhui. [Now 20 confirmed -- 14 in ProMED archive human (26) case list plus 2 in [3] below].

--
