******
[2] China, 6th death
Date: Fri 5 Apr 2013
Source: English news, Xinhua report report [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2013-04/05/c_132286126.htm


East China's Zhejiang Province on Friday [5 Apr 2013] morning reported that a man has died from the H7N9 bird flu, bringing the death toll from the new deadly strain to 6 in the country. The city has reported 3 infections to date, and 2 have died, the Health Bureau of Zhejiang Province said Friday [5 Apr 2013].

According to the health bureau, the 64-year-old man, who is a peasant farmer of Huzhou City, died at hospital after rescue efforts failed on Thursday [4 Apr 2013] night, and it was confirmed he was infected with the H7N9 strain. So far, 55 people who had close contact with him have shown no abnormal symptoms.

China has confirmed 14 H7N9 cases -- 6 in Shanghai, 4 in Jiangsu, 3 in Zhejiang, and one in Anhui -- in the 1st known human infections of this lesser-known strain. [Now 14 confirmed -- see [3] & ProMED archive human (26) below].

Shanghai authorities on Thursday [4 Apr 2013] reported 4 deaths, with Zhejiang now reporting 2.

--
Communicated by:
Ryan McGinnis <digicana@gmail.com>

[3] Jiangsu, new cases
Date: Fri 5 Apr 2013
Source: QQ News [in Chinese, trans. Mod.YMA, edited]
http://news.qq.com/a/20130405/000911.htm


According to the Jiangsu Health Department on 5 Apr 2013, 2 new cases of H7N9 avian influenza infection were confirmed.

The 1st case is a 61-year-old female who lives in Qinhuai District, Nanjing city. She is retired and stays at home. She began to sicken on 20 Mar 2013 and was admitted to a hospital in Nanjing as her symptoms got worse. At present, she is in critical condition and receiving emergency treatments.

On 3 Apr 2013, the laboratory test from Jiangsu provincial CDC revealed nucleic acid weakly positive for H7N9 avian influenza virus. In the morning of 5 Apr 2013, the provincial CDC collected a specimen by deep lung aspiration, which resulted nucleic acid positive for H7N9 avian influenza virus. In the afternoon of 5 Apr 2013, as per the treatment guidelines for human infection with H7N9 avian influenza (1st edition of 2013) issued by the National Health and Family Planning Commission, experts diagnosed this case as H7N9 avian influenza infection. After investigation, 12 close contacts were identified, but none of them have respiratory symptoms.

The 2nd case is a 79-year-old male from Qinhuai District, Nanjing City. He became sick on 21 Mar 2013 and was admitted to a hospital in Nanjing due to severe symptoms. This case is also in critical condition now, and emergency treatment is being provided to this patient.

During the night of 2 Apr 2013, the laboratory from Jiangsu CDC found nucleic acid [from this case] preliminarily tested weakly positive for H7N9 avian influenza infection. Another laboratory test on 4 Apr 2013 also showed nucleic acid weakly positive for H7N9. On the morning of 5 Apr 2013, the provincial CDC collected a specimen by deep lung aspiration, which revealed nucleic acid positive for H7N9 avian influenza virus. In the afternoon of 5 Apr 2013, according to the treatment guidelines for human infection with H7N9 avian influenza (1st edition of 2013) issued by the National Health and Family Planning Commission, experts diagnosed this case as H7N9 avian influenza infection. A total of 53 close contacts were found after investigation, but none of them have fever or respiratory symptoms as of yet.

On the afternoon of 5 Apr 2013, experts were investigating 2 unexplained pneumonia cases (one from Binhu District, Wuxi City and one from Wujiang District, Suzhou City). Due to lack of sufficient evidence, they were diagnosed as suspected cases as per the guidelines mentioned above.

Experts from Jiangsu Health Department are working hard to save the lives of these patients and are implementing epidemic prevention and control measures. Until now, Jiangsu has confirmed 6 cases of H7N9 avian influenza infection.

