[5] Hong Kong, suspected case
Date: Fri 5 Apr 2013
Source: South China Morning Post [edited]
http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1207791/1st-suspected-case-human-h7h9-hong-kong


Hong Kong on Friday [5 Apr 2013] will step up its control measures against the new bird flu strain that has killed 6 people in eastern China after a Hong Kong girl showed flu symptoms following a visit to Shanghai.

The 7-year-old has become the 1st suspected case of the H7N9 bird flu virus in Hong Kong. The girl has now been put in an isolation ward in Queen Elizabeth Hospital for further observation to confirm whether she has contracted the virus. She showed avian flu-like symptoms, including fever, after visiting Shanghai in late March 2013. During the trip, the girl had contact with birds, health officials said. "Respiratory specimens are being taken from the girl, and a rapid test is being conducted," said Dr Dominic Tsang Ngai-chong, the Hospital Authority's chief infection control officer. He added that the results were expected later on Friday [5 Apr 2013].

The suspected case came as Hong Kong officials were trying to ward off any chance of the deadly H7N9 bird flu outbreak spreading to the city. The mainland cases have alerted a Hong Kong that is revisiting lessons from the SARS (severe acute respiratory syndrome) pandemic of 10 years ago.

Secretary for Food and Health Dr Ko Wing-man said the city would step up control measures now. These included enhancing surveillance on poultry imports from the mainland and of travellers at the border. If any poultry or wild birds were to be found infected with avian flu, including the H5 and H7 strains, Ko said the government might order the culling of live poultry stocks in the city. He said Hong Kong's live and frozen chickens mainly come from registered farms in the southern provinces of Guangdong and Hainan, and no stocks were imported from eastern China. More health inspectors will also be deployed to border checkpoints to check the body temperatures of travellers, and more frequent inspection and cleaning will be conducted in markets.

Hong Kong health experts will meet their mainland counterparts on Saturday and Sunday [6-7 Apr 2013] to discuss other control measures, Ko said. The development comes as a 6th person in China died of the virus. The latest fatality was a 64-year-old farmer who died in Huzhou, in the eastern province of Zhejiang, local officials said, according to the state Xinhua news agency.

He was one of the 16 [now 18] confirmed human cases of H7N9 and is the 2nd person from Zhejiang to die from the strain, with the other 4 fatalities in Shanghai, China's commercial hub. In Shanghai, a poultry cull was carried out at the Huhuai market in a western suburb of Shanghai following the discovery of the virus in pigeon samples, Xinhua reported.
[Now all Shanghai poultry markets have been closed -- see [5] above]

[Byline: Lai Ying-kit]

